{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<8 News><Anchor>Students who have crossed the CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] hurdle now have no time to rest as they prepare for essay-writing exams. Preparing for these demanding essay exams has become so challenging that the term 'essay exam expedition' has emerged. Reporter Lee Byeong-hee conducted an in-depth investigation.<Reporter>Student Kim, who lives in Cheonan, South Chungcheong Province. As soon as last month's CSAT ended, he came up to Seoul to find an essay-writing hagwon.[Student Kim/Cheonan, South Chungcheong Province: Seoul definitely has more information than local areas. A few of my (local) friends are attending famous hagwons in the Gangnam [an affluent district in Seoul] area.][Park Woo-jin/Evaluation Director, 'H' College Prep Hagwon: We've been receiving considerably more inquiry calls since CSAT, and the number of enrolled students has been gradually increasing over time.]High school senior Lee, a female student, also came up from Gunsan, North Jeolla Province to attend an essay-writing hagwon. Since college admission is the priority, she has no time to worry about her remaining school classes.[Student Lee/Gunsan, North Jeolla Province: There's nothing to do at school anyway... Right now there are no classes, so attendance isn't that strict, so it's not really a problem.]The issue is that it's difficult for students to receive proper essay-writing instruction at school. Although there's about a month between the CSAT and winter break, most high schools don't offer essay-writing courses, making them virtually in a state of closure.[Kim Yu-ni/High School Senior: These days? We read books, chat, or sleep.] Since the types of essays vary so much by university and department, school teachers express frustration that realistically guiding students is difficult.[Lee Moon-haeng/High School Teacher: I think there's a clear difference between students who receive guidance through hagwon education and those who don't.]The college entrance essay-writing exams are gaining more weight each year. If individual schools find it difficult to provide essay instruction, there are calls for public education to play a more active role, such as by grouping several schools by region to conduct joint essay lectures."
}
```

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<8 News><Anchor>Now that the CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] is over, college admissions agencies are competing to hold university admission information sessions. However, the admission score ranges they present are all different from each other. You need to examine them carefully. This is reporter Lee Byung-hee.<Reporter>This afternoon (2nd) at Jamsil Gymnasium in Seoul. Long lines form as people wait to attend a university admission information session hosted by a college admissions agency. There are about 10,000 attendees in total. Test-takers and parents, thirsty for college admission information, concentrate their full attention on the session content. Despite it being busy work hours, fathers who prioritize their children's college admission information over work are also noticeable. [Cho Seung-rae/Parent: (How did you come here? It's the middle of the day...) I pushed back my company work a bit today... I need to know something too so I can discuss it with my daughter...] However, even for the same university and same department, there are considerable score differences between the placement reference charts released by different admissions agencies, leaving test-takers still confused. Departments with 10 to 15 point differences between admissions agencies are easily found. [Lee Seung-woo/Test-taker: The score differences between hagwons are so large that I don't know which one to trust.] College admissions experts point out that while private admissions agencies' placement charts can be used as reference, homeroom teachers' help is absolutely necessary when making final choices. Separately from private admissions agencies, the Seoul Metropolitan Office of Education also held a large-scale admissions information session for the first time, providing college admission information to test-takers and parents."
}

{
  "translated_title": "Elementary School Faces Controversy for Gathering Students in Auditorium to Identify School Violence Perpetrator",
  "translated_text": "An elementary school in Sacheon is facing controversy after it gathered students in an auditorium for facial identification to find perpetrators of school violence. According to Sacheon City A Elementary School in South Gyeongsang Province on the 15th, the school assembled about 100 sixth-grade male students in the auditorium around 1 PM on the 8th after they finished their final exams, had them close their eyes, and conducted facial identification work to find school violence perpetrators. The incident began on the 7th when the father of first-grader B (age 7) came to the school and complained, saying \"My child was hit on the head by older students near the school while going home after class and had his hagwon tuition money stolen.\" B's father strongly insisted that \"the student who stole my child's money was an older student from this school,\" prompting the school to secretly go around sixth-grade classrooms on the morning of the 8th with the student and parent to conduct facial identification while students were taking tests. However, student B failed to find the face of the student who stole his money. When B's father then threatened the principal, saying \"Find the perpetrating students unconditionally by today,\" the school gathered all students in the auditorium and conducted perpetrator identification work together with student B. Even so, student B was unable to identify the student who stole his money despite looking at all sixth-grade students' faces, and in the process caused a 'commotion' by mistakenly pointing to an innocent student as the perpetrator, leading to counseling with the homeroom teacher. Ultimately, this school has still not found the student who stole B's money, and the incident was reported to police, who visited the school on the 14th to conduct an investigation. The school principal said, \"It's unclear whether the perpetrator is a student from our school or from a nearby middle school,\" adding \"Gathering students to find the perpetrator was reckless, but in that situation, that was the only method available to find the culprit.\" (Sacheon=Yonhap News)"
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<8 News><Anchor>A key area that Seoul National University emphasized for normalizing public education is essay-writing exams. They claim there would be no problem if high schools properly teach integrated subject essay-writing, but what was the reaction from frontline teachers? Reporter Shim Young-gu has the story.<Reporter>Seoul National University announced it will provide essay-writing exam teaching methods to 800 high school teachers starting this winter. This is due to their school policy that hagwon education alone cannot prepare students for 'integrated subject essay-writing exams'.[Kim Kyung-beom/Research Professor, Seoul National University Admissions Office: Creative thinking ability cannot be developed through short-term courses lasting just a few weeks. Ultimately, if this is not accomplished within public education, students will be unable to prepare.]This means they intend to transform high school education into a method where students think about and discuss what they have learned through essay-writing exams. Seoul National University emphasized that frontline teachers must improve their essay-writing instruction abilities for this purpose. However, frontline teachers' reactions were lukewarm.[Sang Wook/Teacher at Busan Science Academy for the Gifted: They say it's absolutely impossible to enter our school through hagwon education alone, but I've been guiding college entrance exams for 20 years, and students who received a lot of hagwon education do get into Seoul National University.][Kim Moon-ho/Teacher at Doho High School in Pohang [a city in North Gyeongsang Province]: They say the problems aren't difficult, but in reality, students find them extremely challenging.]This is because there is woefully insufficient time to prepare and teachers to provide instruction.[Kim Ok-hee/Principal of Buseo Girls' High School in Busan: There are no teachers, and when such a big task is thrown at us, it's very bewildering.]Seoul National University stated it will supplement its admissions policies by reflecting these voices from the educational field."
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<8 News><Anchor>Test-takers who wrote answer choice 2 are immediately protesting vehemently. They are showing signs of taking legal action if the testing organization does not acknowledge the error in the question and re-grade the exam. Reporter Jung Yeon reports.<Reporter>Comments from parents and test-takers are pouring in on the Korea Institute for Curriculum and Evaluation's website. Most are demanding that the exam be re-graded and that both answer choices 2 and 4 be accepted as correct answers for Physics II question 11. Since this question is worth 3 points, what the correct answer is can determine whether a student's grade goes up or down by one level, so test-takers cannot help but feel desperate.[Test-taker: Even looking at the advanced sections of textbooks, it clearly states that ideal gases are polyatomic molecules. Answering according to what's clearly stated should be considered consideration for test-takers.]Some test-takers are also appearing who say they will file a class action lawsuit if re-grading is not conducted. Teachers also point out that test-takers who wrote answer choice 2 should be given relief.[Jeon Young-oh/Entrance exam hagwon director: I think it would be reasonable to also acknowledge students who studied properly as correct. Because I think it's unreasonable for students who received proper instruction to be processed as wrong.]According to explanations from inside and outside legal circles, in cases where CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] grades are divided based on this question, it's possible to apply for an injunction for grade designation.[Kim Chang-gyu/Attorney: I believe it's possible to apply for a stay of execution regarding grade designation, and if the stay of execution application is accepted, relief can be obtained through administrative litigation or administrative appeals.]Since accepting multiple correct answers would cause major chaos such as suspending regular admissions and re-grading, the Korea Institute for Curriculum and Evaluation appears unlikely to reverse its existing position. Ultimately, a class action lawsuit by test-takers who feel they were robbed of 3 points appears unavoidable.Related Information 'Wrong answer controversy' content also appears in textbookscontroversy intensifies CSAT Physics II wrong answer controversytest-takers 'absurd and unfair' Korea Institute for Curriculum and Evaluation 'groundless CSAT wrong answer explanation' controversy Evaluation Institute says 'no problem with correct answer'will class action lawsuit situation spread? Watch SBS News with SBSi's new concept multi-viewer 'Nview'!"
}

{
  "translated_title": "Students Whose Acceptances Were Revoked at Gimpo Foreign Language High School Win Provisional Injunction to Maintain Acceptance Status; Six Students from Myongji and Anyang Foreign Language High Schools Also Win Similar Rulings",
  "translated_text": "Following Gimpo Foreign Language High School acceptance revocation students who gained recognition of their acceptance status through provisional injunction applications, six students who had their acceptances to Myongji Foreign Language High School and Anyang Foreign Language High School revoked have also been temporarily granted recognition of their acceptance status. On the 11th, Civil Division 30 of Suwon District Court (Presiding Judge Lee Hye-gwang) accepted the 'provisional injunction for preservation of acceptance status' filed by parents of students whose Myongji Foreign Language High School acceptances were revoked against the Myongji Educational Foundation, deciding that \"the applicants shall temporarily maintain their acceptance status until the final judgment of the lawsuit to confirm invalidity of acceptance revocation.\" The court also decided on the 'provisional injunction application for suspension of acceptance revocation disposition effectiveness' filed by parents of Anyang Foreign Language High School acceptance revocation students against the Woonseok Educational Foundation, ruling to \"suspend the acceptance revocation disposition until the judgment of the lawsuit to confirm invalidity of acceptance revocation.\" The court transmitted this decision notice to the creditors by fax. In the decision document, the court stated that \"the damage to fairness and reliability of this entrance examination resulted from negligence by education office and foreign language high school entrance exam officials who failed to prevent advance leakage of test questions, and fraudulent acts by Gimpo Foreign Language High School teachers and a hagwon director.\" (Suwon=Yonhap News)"
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<8 News><Anchor>Is what has been revealed this time everything? As you heard, the investigation into the corrupt dealings between specialized high schools and entrance exam hagwons is expected to expand nationwide. Reporter Kim Ho-seon reports.<Reporter>The government and the Grand United Democratic Party have decided through government-party consultations to conduct a fact-finding investigation into the collusive ties between specialized high schools and specialized high school entrance exam hagwons. They are also actively reviewing plans to form a special investigation team in cooperation with the National Police Agency and others. In particular, autonomous private high schools have also been included as subjects for inspection.[Lee Kyung-suk/Grand United Democratic Party lawmaker: We paid attention to the fact that this is related to the formation of collusive relationships between schools and hagwons, such as current teachers creating mock exams for private educational institutions.]Accordingly, the Gimpo Foreign Language High School incident has expanded into a fact-finding investigation of entrance exams for specialized high schools and autonomous private high schools nationwide. Even without leaking test questions, there are criticisms that specialized high schools force hagwon education [Korea's private tutoring industry] by demanding unreasonably high academic standards, so attention is focused on whether supplementary measures will be introduced to address this.[Park Kyung-yang/Policy Committee member, Parents for True Education: They try to test content that students haven't learned in their previous educational stages. This inevitably increases hagwon education.]With the Ministry of Education conducting its own investigation into the operational status of specialized high schools, major changes in specialized high school admissions and operations appear inevitable.Related Information Gimpo Foreign Language High School test question leak incident enters containment phase Foreign language high school question leak teacher: \"We teach through loopholes\" Gimpo Foreign Language High School founder: \"Devastated before even being able to unfold educational dreams\" Universities also involved in 'entrance exam question leaks'... Dance department professors indicted Watch SBS News with SBSi's new concept multi-viewer 'Nview'!"
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "The Seoul Jongno Police Station, which is investigating the leak of CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] score analysis materials, is conducting an investigation into whether there was prior collusion among those involved in the data leak. Police applied for search and seizure warrants for the mobile phone call records of Teacher Cho, who extracted materials from the Ulsan Metropolitan Office of Education on the 8th and transmitted them to three college entrance exam hagwons in Seoul, and hagwon officials. Additionally, they are investigating after receiving the mobile phone call records of Team Leader Kim from G Education Consulting, who extracted the same materials from a Korea Institute for Curriculum and Evaluation employee's email, and the evaluation institute employee."
}

{
  "translated_title": "Teacher Arrested for Stealing and Leaking CSAT Score Analysis Materials",
  "translated_text": "The Seoul Jongno Police Station, which is investigating the leak of CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] score analysis materials, announced on the 18th that it confirmed a school teacher surnamed Cho from a high school in Ulsan had secretly removed related materials from the Ulsan Metropolitan Office of Education and distributed them, and booked Cho without detention on theft charges. According to police, Cho is suspected of removing CSAT score distribution materials and other related documents that were stored at the Ulsan Metropolitan Office of Education on the afternoon of the 8th, then transmitting them by fax to hagwon education [Korea's private tutoring industry] industry officials including Director Jin of Bisang Edu. In police questioning, Cho reportedly stated, \"I stopped by the education office to lecture teachers on college guidance techniques, and discovered CSAT score materials left in an office, so I secretly took them.\" Police explained that besides Director Jin, Cho also handed over the materials to famous college entrance exam companies including D hagwon and J hagwon in Seoul. Police are investigating the possibility that an official from the Ulsan Metropolitan Office of Education handed the materials to Cho, contrary to Cho's statement that he secretly took them. They also plan to investigate whether Cho received compensation from hagwon education industry officials in exchange for handing over the materials. A police official said, \"We confirmed that Director Jin, who received the materials from Cho, then sent them again to Section Chief Lee of K college entrance exam company,\" adding \"It's suspicious whether sharing materials among companies even before distribution has become an industry practice.\" Bisang Edu, a college entrance exam company, caused a controversy over the prior leak of CSAT analysis materials by releasing a press statement on the 9th, the day before CSAT scores were announced, containing CSAT-related information including average scores by subject area. Police have been conducting an investigation believing this incident occurred when Team Leader Kim of G college entrance exam company accessed emails of evaluation center employees to extract materials and delivered them to Director Jin of Bisang Edu through an official at K college entrance exam company. Police plan to continue investigating both the previously known leak route through Kim and the newly revealed route through school teacher Cho, while also investigating whether there are cases of materials being leaked through yet another third route. (Seoul=Yonhap News)"
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "The Seoul Central District Prosecutors' Office Public Security Division 1 conducted search and seizure operations on the 15th at two locations: the election planning office of Seoul Metropolitan Office of Education Superintendent Gong Jeong-taek, who is suspected of illegally raising election funds, and the Jung-gu branch of M hagwon in Jongno operated by hagwon director Mr. Choi. Prosecutors plan to summon Superintendent Gong for questioning this week, following last week's interrogation of his wife regarding suspicions of election fund support through borrowed-name accounts. Superintendent Gong is known to have borrowed or received support totaling approximately 1.8 billion won [approximately $1.35 million USD] from hagwon and private school officials, including 590 million won [approximately $442,000 USD] from Mr. Choi, out of his total election expenses of 2.2 billion won [approximately $1.65 million USD] during the Seoul Metropolitan Office of Education superintendent election last July. Meanwhile, prosecutors reportedly secured evidence through account tracking and email searches showing that the Seoul branch of KTU (Korean Teachers and Education Workers Union, a left-leaning teachers' organization) specifically directed election campaign support for former Seoul Metropolitan Office of Education superintendent candidate Joo Kyung-bok and conducted fundraising activities targeting teachers."
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<8 News><Anchor>Meanwhile, test-takers preparing for university regular admissions are having a very busy weekend. Students and parents are engaged in an 'information war' for regular university admissions applications that begin next Friday. Reporter Kim Jeong-yoon covered this story. PIP close<Reporter>At consultation booths set up by each university, there's a steady stream of students and parents visiting. With regular university admissions starting on the 18th, students are eager to obtain even one more piece of information.[Park Seong-eun/repeat test-taker [a student retaking CSAT after high school graduation] : Because there are so many students with the same scores by score range, we don't know where they'll apply and I don't know where my scores would be advantageous, so securing a lot of information is important. It's an information battle.]This year's regular admissions have become more competitive as the CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] portion has increased with relatively easier questions, and the number of test-takers has increased by about 15% compared to last year. Also, many universities have switched from college-wide recruitment to department-specific recruitment, and some universities have moved to different admission groups, creating more details that need careful attention.[Choi Gwi-ha/parent of high school senior : The ratio is close. It becomes dozens to one, like that. So I think acceptance or rejection will be decided by very small differences.]Experts advise collecting information from various sources and creating one's own application criteria, given that admission methods vary greatly among universities.[Choi Byeong-gi/counseling teacher at Korean Council for University Education : From the student's perspective, the task now is to find the optimal combination with their scores - whether standard scores are advantageous, whether percentile scores are advantageous, what the weighting is for each subject area, and how many percentage points are given as bonus points.]They also emphasize not to rely too heavily on placement charts from private hagwons, and to appropriately utilize the three application opportunities considering one's grades and aptitude.(Video reporting: Lee Yong-han, Video editing: Nam Il)"
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "Housewives in Nowon-gu gather in groups of three to five at a cafe, drinking tea and chatting. The interior looks no different from any other cafe, but what catches the eye are people taking English lessons with native-speaking teachers throughout the cafe. [Oh Seung-ho/Information Library Director: You can chat in the cafe and talk about recent events, and unlike hagwons, you can enjoy leisure activities in a free atmosphere. This is very different from typical hagwons.] Mainly housewives with a strong interest in English visit this place during morning hours. For just 10,000 won [approximately $7.50 USD] per month, they can participate in English lessons offered here twice a week, drawing enthusiastic responses from housewives. [Yoo Sun-ju/Donam-dong, Seoul: I originally loved English, and I like the atmosphere where mothers can freely talk together.] [Baek Su-kyung/Sanggye-dong, Seoul: I build my skills and gain information. I started this initially, but after trying it, I really like it.] This place filled with flower fragrances is a 'flower cafe' where you can drink tea and buy flowers. The interior creates a beautiful atmosphere filled with various types of flowers. The cafe also transforms into an impromptu classroom. Once a week, they gather students directly to hold flower arrangement classes. [Lee Suk/Flower Cafe Owner: After people come here and see beautiful things, some want to learn, so we can directly connect this and sell it as a product. That's how we came to operate a flower arrangement entrepreneurship class.] Housewives respond positively to the fun of learning something new. [Kim Hyun-suk/Bucheon, Gyeonggi Province: Doing flower arrangement in a cafe like this is more free than at a regular flower shop. I don't know if it's because it's the atmosphere I like, but I really love it.] Using milk to create foam and placing it on top of coffee completes an appetizing cappuccino. At a coffee specialty shop in Bundang [an affluent district in Seongnam city], housewives of various ages are taking coffee classes. Here, for just 100,000 won [approximately $75 USD] monthly tuition, you can take coffee classes from professional baristas. All classes are conducted through hands-on practice, from understanding coffee to technical education on operating coffee machines, drawing continuous visits from housewives interested in coffee. [Bae Jae-ran/Student: First of all, the quality of life itself is upgraded and it's healthy and matches well, so the standard of living is fundamentally improved.] [Kim Young-mi/Student: When I didn't know about coffee, I thought you just drank instant coffee. But after brewing it myself, it's really fresh, so I think it's even better.] These unique experiential cafes that housewives visit for leisure activities are gaining attention as thrifty venues where you can enjoy hobbies while having a cup of tea."
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "--The livelihood sector is where ordinary people struggle in their daily lives. For citizens, the most pressing issues are how much their children's tuition will increase and how much housing costs. According to a survey conducted from November 21st for two days targeting 1,000 adult men and women nationwide on what the most urgent livelihood issues the president should address are: 4th place - reducing the burden of education costs (12.4%), 3rd place - real estate stability including housing prices (12.6%), 2nd place - price stability including oil prices (24.9%), 1st place - job creation and unemployment resolution (33.6%). The president seems to have set next year's economic growth forecast at 4-5%, and the Korea Economic Research Institute has set it at 5.5%. Economic indicators are improving, but ordinary people don't feel it. When might the economic sentiment improve for ordinary people? This is exactly what I'm thinking a lot about. Currently, economic growth is recovering fastest among OECD (Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development) countries and will be the highest next year as well, so the IMF (International Monetary Fund) and OECD say it will be 4.5%. I expect it will be slightly revised upward by year-end. I think next year's economy will be around 5%. However, on one hand, looking at various indicators, they say we should use exit strategies, but I don't agree. Even though our economy has good numbers and is leading among OECD countries, there are various variables in the global economy. Problems have arisen in Dubai, and if a financial crisis occurs in any developed country, the ripple effects will come immediately. If the global economy declines, we won't be able to sell our products either. It's impossible to gauge how much oil and gas prices will rise. They say oil prices will be around $80 next year, but I think they'll rise to $100. External forecasts also expect it to be around 5%. Companies and small businesses feel it first. For ordinary people's sentiment, it will probably take until the first half of next year. In the first half, we'll start the so-called Hope Work project from February and do internships again. Youth unemployment is now slightly over 8%. In the US and Europe, it's nearly 20%. They say we're better than developed countries, but the government's immediate task is how to create jobs. If the economic growth rate improves, corporate investment will begin, and domestic demand is recovering a bit faster than the government predicted, so it will probably improve somewhat, but the government is trying to take the lead in creating good jobs among livelihood measures and job creation. Because small and medium enterprises can't find 200,000 people. How to match people who want jobs with those who want to hire - when they don't match well, we have specific plans for the government to provide retraining and customized training to match them. Since we've become a country that provides aid, if we transfer our experience overseas, 20,000 young people will go abroad annually. We're concentrating support on small and medium enterprises and startups. Because there are government efforts to create opportunities for young people, they'll be able to feel it in the second half. [Image enlargement] --You said next year's economy will smoothly reach about 5%, and that we recovered quickly without major damage compared to the global financial crisis, but there are many questions about whether the fundamentals of our economy are recovering. I understand there are many concerns about side effects if we provide short-term stimulus without fundamental improvement being supported - what perspective do you have? In fact, in the first half and third quarter, there was heavy dependence on government fiscal spending. To continue growing, private corporate investment must now follow. That's how demand is created. We were very worried entering the fourth quarter. We thought it would go into negative growth, but fortunately it was positive growth. Looking at the content, private sector began investing much better than we worried about in the third quarter, and private consumption is also increasing a bit. Because household savings are very weak, there are problems with savings. Can companies continue to activate investment in the fourth quarter? Companies must have something worth investing in - they don't do it just because the government tells them to. Listening to economic organizations, companies were passive about investment in the second quarter, but by the end of the fourth quarter they're doing it actively. We're continuously monitoring fundamentals, private investment, consumption, savings, etc. Foreign countries evaluate that Korea is doing things soundly. By 2014-2015, fiscal deficits will also reverse and become surpluses. The government is monitoring very carefully and hasn't disbanded the emergency economic countermeasures committee yet. The perspective is that exit measures should be taken a bit more slowly. [Image enlargement] --What you did well was hosting the G20 summit, and what you didn't do well was tax cuts for the rich. Since becoming president, I'm misunderstood as being pro-big business and pro-rich, but fundamentally I'm instinctively not that way. Big companies must do well to create jobs. You could say I'm pro-market, but I'm pro-jobs. Tax cuts are about creating jobs. 65% of tax cut benefits go to small and medium enterprises. To call this policy for the rich is a misunderstanding. It's frustrating, but I have firm convictions. (Tax cuts) create jobs and stimulate domestic demand, I believe. --When talking about pro-ordinary people policies, you gave the example of the Smile Foundation, but there are concerns about moral hazard if people just take money without doing business and don't repay. This is part of ordinary people's policy, but the people suffering most are those doing business in traditional markets and on the streets - these people can't engage in financial transactions. It applies to people doing small and medium business, but benefits don't properly reach people doing street business. When urgent, they end up using private loans of 1 million won [approximately $750 USD] or 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD], and it grows to 10 times the principal. The foreign term for this is microcredit. We liked the name 'Smile' so we called it Smile, where large corporations and financial institutions voluntarily put forward 1.3 trillion won [approximately $1 billion USD] and companies do it themselves. Each company puts forward a certain amount, giving these people from 3 million won [approximately $2,300 USD] to 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD], with some places giving up to 10 million won [approximately $7,500 USD]. It hasn't been long since we started this, but many people say the purpose is good but ask what about moral hazard. Two weeks ago I went to an event venue where an elderly woman wanted to meet me, but security wouldn't let her, so we brought her over. This woman was making fish-shaped pastries in Jongno but couldn't make them anymore because she didn't have 3 million won [approximately $2,300 USD]. She borrowed 3 million won [approximately $2,300 USD] to make fish-shaped pastries again and came to thank me. She said she'd used private loans all her life, but this was the first time receiving low-interest financing. She said what she wants to do now is give fish-shaped pastries to poor people who in the past could only look at them without being able to buy them, since she received the country's grace. I was moved. I tell people who talk about moral hazard: People who borrow 3 million won [approximately $2,300 USD] or 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD] absolutely won't default. They might repay a bit late though. But there are people who default on 5 billion won [approximately $3.8 million USD] or 10 billion won [approximately $7.5 million USD]. Because I'm confident that people who borrow 3 million won [approximately $2,300 USD] or 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD] do repay, this system should be expanded in the future. From companies and financial institutions that participated, about 700-800 billion won [approximately $530-600 million USD] remains, so we'll probably create nearly 2 trillion won [approximately $1.5 billion USD] in Smile Finance for loans. [Image enlargement] --What you did well was hosting the G20 summit, and what you didn't do well was tax cuts for the rich. Since becoming president, I'm misunderstood as being pro-big business and pro-rich, but fundamentally I'm instinctively not that way. Big companies must do well to create jobs. You could say I'm pro-market, but I'm pro-jobs. Tax cuts are about creating jobs. 65% of tax cut benefits go to small and medium enterprises. To call this policy for the rich is a misunderstanding. It's frustrating, but I have firm convictions. (Tax cuts) create jobs and stimulate domestic demand, I believe. --When talking about pro-ordinary people policies, you gave the example of the Smile Foundation, but there are concerns about moral hazard if people just take money without doing business and don't repay. This is part of ordinary people's policy, but the people suffering most are those doing business in traditional markets and on the streets - these people can't engage in financial transactions. It applies to people doing small and medium business, but benefits don't properly reach people doing street business. When urgent, they end up using private loans of 1 million won [approximately $750 USD] or 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD], and it grows to 10 times the principal. The foreign term for this is microcredit. We liked the name 'Smile' so we called it Smile, where large corporations and financial institutions voluntarily put forward 1.3 trillion won [approximately $1 billion USD] and companies do it themselves. Each company puts forward a certain amount, giving these people from 3 million won [approximately $2,300 USD] to 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD], with some places giving up to 10 million won [approximately $7,500 USD]. It hasn't been long since we started this, but many people say the purpose is good but ask what about moral hazard. Two weeks ago I went to an event venue where an elderly woman wanted to meet me, but security wouldn't let her, so we brought her over. This woman was making fish-shaped pastries in Jongno but couldn't make them anymore because she didn't have 3 million won [approximately $2,300 USD]. She borrowed 3 million won [approximately $2,300 USD] to make fish-shaped pastries again and came to thank me. She said she'd used private loans all her life, but this was the first time receiving low-interest financing. She said what she wants to do now is give fish-shaped pastries to poor people who in the past could only look at them without being able to buy them, since she received the country's grace. I was moved. I tell people who talk about moral hazard: People who borrow 3 million won [approximately $2,300 USD] or 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD] absolutely won't default. They might repay a bit late though. But there are people who default on 5 billion won [approximately $3.8 million USD] or 10 billion won [approximately $7.5 million USD]. Because I'm confident that people who borrow 3 million won [approximately $2,300 USD] or 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD] do repay, this system should be expanded in the future. From companies and financial institutions that participated, about 700-800 billion won [approximately $530-600 million USD] remains, so we'll probably create nearly 2 trillion won [approximately $1.5 billion USD] in Smile Finance for loans. [Image enlargement] --(Citizen) I'm approaching graduation and trying hard to find employment, but it's difficult. You mentioned venture startups to resolve youth unemployment, but startups realistically have few success cases and are difficult. They don't meet the income and welfare levels we hope for, so rather than just telling us to lower our expectations, wouldn't it be right to present fundamental solutions? Many people say to lower your expectations, but I don't use such words. When I was young and heard that, I felt bad. Don't lower them, match them. If you go to big companies, there are often cases where you repeat the same predetermined tasks. Small and medium enterprises might be disappointing, but the scope is wide so there are many things to experience. They hire new employees but these days they hire all experienced workers. In such times, you can gain experience at small and medium enterprises and go to other companies. Looking at people doing small and medium business, the salary is decent but young people don't apply, they say. Many young people's majors don't match, so the government provides training for that. There are 6-month and 1-year courses with 600,000-1 million won [approximately $450-750 USD] support for free education systems established nationwide. Ventures literally require challenge. You might fail, but don't fear failure. If you fear failure and do nothing, you can't gain experience. You can gain experience and mature even through failure. I actually joined a small and medium enterprise. That small enterprise later became a large enterprise, but people asked why I was going to such a company. Still, I went to the small enterprise, felt rewarded, and had the experience of growing as the company grew. I'm saying to also look at small and medium enterprises. Aren't service industries good jobs? 40-50 are created while manufacturing creates less than 10. We'll foster service industries so many young people can enter. --I'm a company employee in my 30s. I tried to apply for the Bogeumjari Housing newlywed special sale, but couldn't apply because I don't have children. Friends also give up applying due to strict conditions. You say you're focusing on housing stability for ordinary people, but I wish you'd prepare ordinary people's measures more satisfactorily. I moved 8 times in 3 years after marriage. I was evicted every 6 months. Later I went to a 20-pyeong apartment and had four children. I promised to build rental and sale apartments that can be used long-term for 10, 20 years or more near downtown, close to workplaces, and give priority to people who worked all their lives but couldn't own homes even if they're not newlyweds. When trying to implement policies, suddenly many people said they were getting married and many newlyweds came out, making it unmanageable. I can't investigate whether someone is pregnant. We're taking measures to show consideration to those who say they're pregnant, but Bogeumjari Housing doesn't end at once - it comes out twice a year. The government is reviewing giving the same opportunities to those who are definitely pregnant. But they shouldn't speculate and sell. We don't want speculation since it's so cheap, new green buildings with low management fees, and high-quality buildings. [Image enlargement] --In the past, there were many kidnappings, so parents worried a lot. Now with incidents like the 'Cho Doo-soon case,' those with daughters don't feel at ease. As parents, we worry about preventing repeat offenses and whether we can send our children outside with peace of mind. It's truly bewildering. We talk about becoming a first-class country, becoming a developed country, but becoming developed isn't just about income rising. We must become developed by eliminating things like child sexual crimes and living comfortably. Among all crimes, I think child sexual crimes are the most immoral. Child sexual offenders should be isolated from society for life. In our country, sentences for drug offenders and child sexual offenders are lower than in other developed countries. We should raise these and establish government measures so that everywhere these people move, it can be announced what kind of people they are, so they can't establish footing. We should eliminate such heinous criminals and are reviewing creating 'caretakers' for children going to school, where neighborhood grandmothers take them, and mothers with time take turns caring for others' children and their own children without distinction. --My ideal type is a woman who cooks well. While watching TV, I saw CNN news where First Lady Kim Yoon-ok was introducing our food. Does the First Lady actually cook well, and does the president also cook sometimes? I don't cook well. I haven't had opportunities to cook, but I'm good at making ramen. My wife is probably watching TV now. I should say she cooks well - how would it work if I said she doesn't? My wife makes good dakgangjeong [sweet and sour chicken]. She's interested in cooking, but following the Korean Wave, we want to spread Korean food worldwide as healthy food, so the Korean Wave spreads food culture along with arts and culture. --One of our children is a college student, but went to auxiliary police service so we're relieved, but when they were middle and high school students, we thought our backs would break from hagwon education costs. They say when going to middle school, you're fortunate if you don't go into debt. Every time the president announces hagwon education cost reduction measures, the strange phenomenon of hagwon education costs rising occurs. Are there hagwon education cost reduction measures? Education can be called Korea's chronic disease. For 30 years we've talked about equalized education, but we send kids to hagwon education because university admissions can't be equalized, so there's no choice but to receive hagwon education. We must change the university admission system. Shouldn't it disappear if we say you can enter without receiving hagwon education? Instead of selecting by grades, if someone received hagwon education and got 90 points, and someone who didn't receive hagwon education got 80 points, the system should accept the 80-point person. This evaluates that if this person had received hagwon education, they would have scored not just 90 but higher - they have potential. It comprehensively evaluates whether

{
  "translated_title": "Sharp Divisions Over Foreign Language High School Reform Plan at National Assembly Discussion",
  "translated_text": "At a discussion forum titled 'Problems and Improvement Directions Following the Announcement of Foreign Language High School Reform Plan' held on the morning of the 22nd at the National Assembly Members' Office Building by Grand National Party lawmaker Jung Du-eon, opinions sharply divided for and against the government's reform plan. The reform plan announced by the government on the 10th requires foreign language high schools to either maintain their current system or choose to convert to one of the following by 2012: international high schools, autonomous public high schools, or autonomous private high schools. At the discussion forum, the Ministry of Education, Science and Technology and the Korean Federation of Teachers' Associations argued for an end to controversy over the reform plan, calling it \"a product of careful consideration that gathered opinions from all sectors,\" while opponents harshly criticized the government's reform plan as a \"stopgap measure.\" Kim Seong-cheon, deputy director of the Policy Research Institute at 'The World Without Worry about Hagwon Education,' argued for new alternative measures in a presentation paper released prior to the discussion, describing the government's foreign language high school reform plan as \"giving fever reducers instead of surgery\" and stating that \"particularly the acceptance of the admissions officer system reflects foreign language high schools' position in its entirety.\" Deputy Director Kim proposed that for substantial foreign language high school reform to be achieved:  the legal status of foreign language high schools should be converted to specialized high schools, autonomous schools, or general schools, and  restrictions should be placed on foreign language high schools' selection authority to resolve hagwon education problems related to foreign language high school entrance exams. Gong Gi-taek, a teacher at Suwon Dongwoo Girls' High School, harshly criticized the plan, saying \"This reform plan, far from calming the hagwon education frenzy, will further excite the hagwon education market,\" and drew attention by stating that \"If Education Minister Ahn Byung-man intends to persist with his stubborn insistence on maintaining foreign language high schools, he should step down from his ministerial position and return to a foreign language high school.\" Shin Soon-yong, co-representative of the Parents' Coalition for Realizing Human Education, argued for converting foreign language high schools to regular schools, stating that \"educational reform has been derailed by pressure from the privileged class\" and that \"the absorptive power of the hagwon education market exceeds ordinary people's imagination, making it difficult to reduce hagwon education regardless of what reform plan limited to selection methods is produced.\" In contrast, Seong Sam-je, director of the Ministry of Education's School System Planning Division, predicted that \"making foreign language high schools truly foreign language high school-like is one of the core elements of the government's foreign language high school measures\" and that \"it will not be easy for foreign language high schools to prepare for university entrance exams while ignoring foreign language specialties in the future.\" Director Seong further emphasized that \"the message the government is sending to the hagwon education market through this announcement is that 'we will not allow the hagwon education market to seize hegemony in our country's middle and high school entrance exams.'\" Lee Myeong-gyun, director of the Policy Research Office at the Korean Federation of Teachers' Associations, stated that \"extreme arguments for abolishing foreign language high schools provide no help to our education and cannot be a fundamental solution for hagwon education costs\" and that \"since the government reform plan has been carefully considered, wasteful and anti-educational controversy should come to an end.\" (Seoul=Yonhap News)"
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<8 News><Anchor>This year's CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] scores have been tallied as significantly lower than last year. Mid-to-lower tier students are expected to face fierce strategic competition, and controversy is arising over the effectiveness of EBS [Educational Broadcasting System, Korea's state-run educational media]'s CSAT linkage policy. Reporter Choi Woo-cheol reports. PIP close<Reporter>This year's CSAT, which was said to be slightly more difficult than last year. When the preliminary scoring results were revealed, the actual score decline exceeded expectations. According to admissions consulting firms' analysis of preliminary scoring results, all subjectsKorean language, mathematics, and foreign languageshowed clear grade declines. For the math section taken by science track students, the first-grade cutline dropped by as much as 10 points. Therefore, both test-takers and school teachers prefer applying to lower-tier schools as a safe strategy. In particular, universities targeted by mid-to-lower tier applicants are expected to see higher competition rates, and strategic competition among test-takers is expected to be fierce. [Lee Seok-rok/Director of Megastudy College Admissions Research Institute: Mid-to-lower tier students are expected to apply to lower-tier schools as a safe strategy, so they need to carefully review whether there are weightings by reflected subject areas, and whether standard scores versus percentiles are advantageous or disadvantageous.] Despite EBS [Educational Broadcasting System, Korea's state-run educational media] materials being linked to over 70% of CSAT questions, the decline in CSAT scores is raising questions about the effectiveness of the EBS linkage policy. [Ahn Ga-hyeong/Baehwa Girls' High School 3rd year: If something we haven't seen comes out, it's just like solving a new problem, so even if it's linked, we might not be able to solve everything.] This has led to criticism that it only increases the learning burden on test-takers. [Current high school senior homeroom teacher: If we're talking about similar passages, it's the same with other workbooks too. We have to teach EBS [Educational Broadcasting System, Korea's state-run educational media] materials separately and even create test questions, so we've given students double or triple the burden.] This CSAT ultimately showed that high scores are only possible through in-depth study of EBS [Educational Broadcasting System, Korea's state-run educational media] materials, raising concerns that the EBS linkage policy, which was introduced to suppress hagwon education [Korea's private tutoring industry], may actually expand hagwon education. (Video reporting: Seol Chi-hwan, Kim Tae-hoon, Video editing: Wi Won-yang)"
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<8 News><Anchor>A plan is being reviewed to change high school GPA [school records] to absolute evaluation starting in 2014, when current 6th graders enter high school. While the purpose is to reduce hagwon education [private tutoring industry] costs, there are quite a few anticipated problems with this approach as well. Reporter Choi Woo-cheol reports. PIP close<Reporter>High school students suffer from fierce grade competition where even a 1-point difference on school tests can flip their GPA grades.[Kim Dong-gyun/Seoul Sehwa High School 1st year: Grades keep changing by just 1-2 points. That inevitably creates competition. It seems like friendships get worse too...]The current high school GPA 9-grade system using relative evaluation, which causes such excessive burden and hagwon education, is expected to transition to absolute evaluation starting in 2014. The curriculum advancement research team formed by the Ministry of Education, Science and Technology presented as a likely alternative a method that would keep raw scores and standard deviations in student records while removing class rankings. The evaluation levels would also be divided not into the traditional excellent-good-fair-poor-fail system, but into categories like 'very excellent' and 'excellent,' with high evaluation scores given without ratio limitations to those who meet the criteria. Since standard deviations by school would be provided, there would be less concern about grade inflation, but the problem is that discrimination ability would inevitably decline.[Lee Man-gi/Uway Central Education Evaluation Director: If absolute evaluation reduces the discrimination ability of school records, and CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] is also made easier and its discrimination ability declines, universities will likely strengthen essay-writing exams, interviews, and aptitude tests.] There are also high concerns about a balloon effect where hagwon education for CSAT and essay-writing exams would expand if the weight of school records decreases.[Kim Seung-hyun/No Worries About Hagwon Education (current school teacher): If diversification of high school curricula and changes in the college entrance exam environment are not established as prerequisites, the absolute evaluation discussions currently being raised are likely to be rendered powerless.] The government plans to finalize its plan based on the research team's proposal after going through a multifaceted public opinion gathering process.(Video coverage: Kim Seong-il, Video editing: Wi Won-yang)"
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "Five organizations including No More Worry About Hagwon Education [a civic group advocating for public education reform and reduction of hagwon dependence] and Good Teachers Movement have announced they will begin a 'Citizens Design Universities' movement for citizens to directly create alternatives for university system reform. Through this movement, these organizations plan to comprehensively address university specialization plans, university curriculum innovation, university entrance exam system improvement, and resolution of university ranking problems. These organizations will hold a launch ceremony on the 20th at 6 PM in Myeong-dong and plan to unveil a 'draft university system reform plan' that they have prepared over the past two years through various discussion forums. They stated they plan to receive review opinions from citizens and experts from all walks of life, hold nationwide touring public hearings early next year, and then continue with legislative petition movements."
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<Anchor> Today (26th) we examine hagwon education [Korea's private tutoring industry] measures as part of our series exploring the tasks and solutions for the incoming Park Geun-hye administration. The key is reducing hagwon education through normalizing public education, but this is not as easy as it sounds. Reporter Kim Yun-su reports. PIP close <Reporter> President-elect Park Geun-hye identified advanced learning as the biggest factor driving hagwon education. She pledged to normalize public education by legally prohibiting exam questions that induce advanced learning. [Park Geun-hye/President-elect, November 21st, Education Policy Announcement: We will prohibit test questions that exceed the school curriculum in various exams and college entrance exams, and will impose strong penalties for violations.] To block advanced learning through law, clear standards for advanced learning must first be established to reduce confusion in educational settings. [Kim Dong-seok/Korean Federation of Teachers' Associations spokesperson: Since the standards for determining whether something constitutes advanced learning are ambiguous, sufficient discussion processes in school settings must be a prerequisite.] President-elect Park also presented a plan to introduce an 'all-day school' system in elementary schools. The plan is to reduce demand for private hagwons by providing after-school programs at school until 5 PM for elementary students who want them, and especially until 10 PM for children of dual-income families. To achieve this, measures to secure student safety at night must be prepared in advance along with expanding teaching staff to prevent side effects. President-elect Park also promised a 'free semester system' that eliminates exams for one semester to give middle school students opportunities for career exploration. However, there are concerns that the 'free semester' could deteriorate into a 'playing semester,' lowering students' academic performance and actually encouraging hagwon education. The voice from educational settings is that the decision on whether to introduce this system should be made after carefully weighing the pros and cons through pilot implementation rather than full-scale implementation. (Video coverage: Je Il, Video editing: Chae Cheol-ho)"
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<Anchor> The predicted results for the 2013 College Scholastic Ability Test [CSAT, Korea's national university entrance exam] have been released. Korean language scores are expected to rise significantly, while Math Type Na and foreign language scores are expected to drop somewhat. Reporter Woo Sang-wook reports. PIP close <Reporter> Test-takers who have finished preliminary CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] scoring cannot hide their disappointment. [Kim Ye-ji/Test-taker: It dropped much more than expected, more than in September (mock exam).] [Song Ga-eun/Test-taker: For now, I'm going to submit applications regardless of minimum grade requirements, but I'm thinking of applying to safer, lower-tier schools.] College entrance exam specialist institutions analyzed that the Grade 1 cutoff for the Korean language section will rise by about 4 points in raw scores compared to last year. On the other hand, they predicted that Math Type Na for liberal arts students will drop by about 4 points, and foreign language by about 5 points. The analysis suggests that CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] discrimination power has increased compared to last year, given the difficulty of English and math. [Lee Young-deok/Daesung Hagwon College Entrance Strategy Director: Since a new CSAT will be introduced next year, test-takers will have strong psychology for safe, lower-tier applications, but since CSAT discrimination power has also increased, they need to make at least one ambitious application out of three opportunities.] If CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] scores fall short of expectations, students must put all their effort into preparing for essay-writing exams and interviews. This year, each university is expected to create essay-writing exam questions within the scope of textbooks or EBS [Educational Broadcasting System, Korea's state-run educational media] materials. [Kang Seok-jun/Seoul Metropolitan Office of Education Essay Support Team School Teacher: Training to accurately analyze essay topics and training to accurately write what universities require in the content presented in essay topics is necessary.] Experts also advise that to broaden school selection options, students should faithfully prepare for final exams to improve their school records. (Video coverage: Bae Moon-san, Noh In-sik, Video editing: Kim Tae-hoon)"
}

{
  "translated_title": "NEAT [National English Ability Test] to Replace CSAT English and Reduce Hagwon Education",
  "translated_text": "<Anchor> NEAT, short for National English Ability Test. It comprehensively tests English ability across four areas: reading, listening, speaking, and writing. The government is planning to replace the CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] English test with this NEAT, and furthermore reduce English hagwon education. What kind of test is it exactly? Reporter Shin Seung-i will explain. PIP close <Reporter> A language lab at a high school in Seoul. Construction work is underway to install partitions so it can be used as a National English Ability Test, or NEAT, testing site. When the terminals here are connected to the Korea Institute for Curriculum and Evaluation server, test questions are uploaded in real time. When students input their answers, they are immediately transmitted to the evaluation institute and assessment is completed. [Lee Jeong-won/Computer Teacher at Daedong Tax High School: Normally this is used for student practice during class hours, and on the day NEAT testing is conducted, students receive and solve problems directly at these seats.] The government began developing NEAT in 2008. It started with the intention of improving the current state of English education where students cannot properly speak or write a single word of English even after studying for 10 years. The plan is to entrust question development entirely to school teachers. The intention is to reduce English hagwon education by creating questions that students can do well on if they properly receive school education alone. [Shin Dong-gwang/English Test Development Director at Korea Institute for Curriculum and Evaluation: Teachers handle all question development and grading, and since all teachers are certified, we believe preparation will be possible without relying on hagwon education.] Results from the first and second NEAT tests show that over 17% of test-takers received A grades in all four areas. An A grade corresponds to around 800 points on TOEIC, 100 points on TOEFL, and 708 points on TEPS. While being easier could reduce the burden of English studying, concerns about discriminatory power are also being raised. The government plans to reach a conclusion around the end of this year on how to incorporate NEAT into university admissions. (Video reporting: Hwang In-seok, Joo Beom, Video editing: Kim Gyeong-yeon)"
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<Anchor> A first-instance court has sentenced Kim Ha-ju, chairman of Younghoon International Middle School who was indicted and detained on charges of admissions fraud, to a heavy sentence of 4 years and 6 months. Reporter Choi Woo-cheol reports. PIP close <Reporter> This is a hotel in Gangbuk-gu, Seoul [a district in northern Seoul]. Four Younghoon International Middle School teachers conducted entrance evaluations here for three days in early December last year. [Hotel staff: You used it on December 7th last year. At that time, you used the 3rd and 4th floors.] They manipulated grades by giving perfect scores in subjective assessment areas to applicants designated by Chairman Kim Ha-ju. With just his instructions, they put students who ranked below 640th in academic performance and were outside the top 5 times the admission quota into the acceptance range in batches. The court recognized Chairman Kim's crime of taking bribes of tens of millions of won [approximately $15,000-75,000 USD] from parents and instructing the manipulation, sentencing him to 4 years and 6 months in prison and ordering him to forfeit 100 million won [approximately $75,000 USD]. The court stated the reason for the severe punishment was that he did not merely provide convenience to a few, but made students and parents who wanted good education into victims. [Do Young-oh/Seoul Northern District Court Planning Judge: This ruling is intended to severely punish hagwon officials who damaged and disrupted educational order and parents who solicited fraudulent admission for their children.] Grade manipulation for Lee Jae-yong Samsung Electronics Vice Chairman's son was also revealed as fact. The teachers raised scores for 3 students who passed as socially disadvantaged candidates, including Vice Chairman Lee Jae-yong's son, and lowered scores for 13 students who had higher grades than them. In contrast, it was revealed that they conspired to select only one student from child protection facilities who could pass the socially disadvantaged candidate track each year. The administrative director who actively participated in grade manipulation received a prison sentence, while 4 parents and teachers received suspended sentences. (Video coverage: Ha Ryung, Video editing: Oh No-young)"
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<Anchor> In this year's early admission round for university entrance exams, plagiarism in personal statements appears to have decreased compared to last year. Rather than applicants becoming more honest, this is largely due to the hagwon education [Korea's private tutoring industry] market having already shifted from plagiarism to ghostwriting services. Reporter Kim Kyung-hee investigated this story. PIP close <Reporter> When writing personal statements for university admissions, copying or patchworking from the internet can lead to disaster. This is because a similarity detection system has been introduced that can catch similar content across three years' worth of application documents. Content identical to others is immediately highlighted in red. This year, similarity checks were applied to all universities implementing admissions officer screening programs, and as a result, plagiarism in personal statements and teacher recommendation letters decreased significantly compared to last year. [Choi Chang-wan/Director of University Admissions Support, KCUE: Universities will verify once more, and based on those results, they will either deduct points or make a decision to cancel admission.] However, the problem is that ghostwriting is becoming popular rather than easily detectable plagiarism. Related hagwons tempt students by saying that while plagiarism can be caught, their customized ghostwriting services have no possibility of detection. [Personal statement ghostwriter: The probability that my method will match someone else's is almost zero. Because I composed it by listening to the student's story...] Universities also maintain that they have no way to respond to ghostwriting. [University official: Currently, because there's no conclusive evidence, even if there are cases where ghostwriting is suspected, it's difficult to reflect that in the evaluation.] The introduction of more sophisticated systems for fair admissions is urgently needed. (Video reporting: Lee Seung-hwan, Video editing: Kim Jong-mi)"
}

{
  "translated_title": "Seoul Metropolitan Office of Education Uncovers 135 Cases of Private School Corruption Through Comprehensive Audit",
  "translated_text": "The Seoul Metropolitan Office of Education conducted comprehensive audits of 12 private school foundations and their 45 affiliated schools over three months starting last July, uncovering 135 cases of private school corruption. The education office filed criminal charges with prosecutors against 5 school staff members whose misconduct was particularly severe and 5 company representatives who conducted facility construction without proper licenses. Additionally, 14 people received disciplinary action, 234 received warnings, and 92 received cautions. The office also demanded institutional warnings for 21 schools and ordered the recovery or preservation of 974 million won [approximately $740,000 USD]. According to the audit results, a principal who was the founder of a private elementary school foundation in Seoul was caught processing 96 million won [approximately $73,000 USD] in personal foreign car repair costs and fuel expenses through the school's accounting system, and was referred to prosecutors on charges of embezzlement. Also uncovered in this audit was a school foundation that continued to allow a current high school teacher to remain in the classroom despite being indicted by prosecutors in 2009 for illegally leaking joint academic assessment questions to entrance exam hagwons 20 times. Other corruption cases uncovered included illegal English education for 1st and 2nd grade elementary students, conducting specific religious education during regular curriculum hours, improper hiring of new teachers, paying foundation staff salaries from school accounts, and improper private contracts for facility construction. The Seoul Metropolitan Office of Education stated that chronic private school corruption continues unabated and announced plans to strengthen audits of private schools."
}

{
  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "<Anchor> The Seoul Metropolitan Office of Education announced the results of comprehensive audits conducted on 45 private schools. Various private school corruption scandals continue unabated, including foundation board chairs using school accounts for personal purposes. Reporter Jeong Hye-jin reports. <Reporter> The Seoul Metropolitan Office of Education conducted audits on 12 private school foundations and their 45 affiliated schools over a three-month period starting last July. In this audit, the city education office uncovered 135 cases of private school corruption, referred 10 individuals with serious violations to the prosecution, and ordered the recovery of 970 million won [approximately $730,000 USD]. One principal, who was the founder of a private elementary school foundation, was caught having processed 96 million won [approximately $72,000 USD] in personal foreign car repair costs and fuel expenses through the school's accounts. This principal was referred to the prosecution on charges of embezzlement in the course of duty. Another private elementary school that gave long-serving teachers 1.9 million won [approximately $1,430 USD] golden lucky keys and spent 51 million won [approximately $38,000 USD] including 300,000 won [approximately $225 USD] Teachers' Day encouragement money was also found through the audit to have misappropriated school budget. Also caught in this audit was a school foundation that continued to allow a high school teacher to remain in the classroom even after the prosecution indicted the teacher for unauthorized leaking of joint academic assessment problems to college entrance exam hagwons 20 times in 2009. The Seoul Metropolitan Office of Education stated that chronic private school corruption is not decreasing and announced plans to strengthen audits of private schools."
}

{
  "translated_title": "High School Final Exam Paper Leak Incident in Yeosu, South Jeolla Province Sparks Investigation",
  "translated_text": "A final exam paper leak incident occurred at a high school in Yeosu, South Jeolla Province, prompting the school to launch an investigation. According to H High School in Yeosu and parents, during final exams conducted from the 8th to 11th, a second-year student identified as 'A' received leaked exam papers for a specific subject and was discovered sharing them with some friends by another student, who took photos with a mobile phone and reported it to the school. The school immediately began an investigation and confirmed that Teacher B, who was in charge of the subject, had leaked the exam papers to Student A, with both parties admitting to their actions. As a result, the school imposed 'disciplinary expulsion' on Student A and suspended Teacher B from duty, with plans to take measures such as dismissal against Teacher B once the investigation is completed. Meanwhile, some parents and hagwon officials have raised suspicions, claiming there have been many cases at this school that suggest exam paper leaks, causing controversy. One parent argued, 'There are suspicions of exam paper leaks, such as some teachers' children showing significant differences of more than 5 grade levels between mock exam and school records [GPA] scores,' adding 'In the fierce competition of college entrance exams [university admissions], manipulating school records to gain admission through the regular admission process should never happen again.' In response, a school official stated, 'We are conducting an investigation into this exam paper leak incident based on the parties' admission,' and 'If additional suspicions are raised, we plan to take strict measures based on the investigation results for those matters as well.'"
}

{
  "translated_title": "Report Reveals Nationwide 'Ranking-Based' Competitive Education Practices in Schools",
  "translated_text": "\"Students ranked in the top 50 of the entire school are made to study in glass-walled study rooms. They say it's to let other kids see and get motivated, but it's absurd and upsetting.\" (Anyang-Bucheon area, Gyeonggi Province) \"There are schools that assign dormitory rooms based on grades. Students who actually live far away don't get to benefit from the dormitory.\" (Seongnam-Bundang area, Gyeonggi Province) The civic organization No More Worry About Private Education [Nowoori] investigated the reality of competitive ranking-based education in schools and found that front-line high schools continue to provide unfair privileges to high-achieving students and promote advanced learning and hagwon education fever. No More Worry About Private Education disclosed the regional status of ranking-based education across 17 provincial and metropolitan education offices, surveyed over the past year while touring 22 cities nationwide. When this organization analyzed 151 reports from parents, students, and teachers nationwide, \"providing unfair privileges to high-achieving students\" was the most common form of \"ranking-based\" education with 32 cases. This was followed by \"classes and various competitions that encourage advanced learning and hagwon education\" with 16 cases, and \"mandatory participation in after-school classes or self-study\" with 12 cases. A parent from Seoul's Gangnam 3-gu area [the three most affluent districts in Gangnam] whose child attends an autonomous private high school said, \"The supplementary materials for 1st-year basic subjects are CSAT [College Scholastic Ability Test, Korea's national university entrance exam] Perfect Score and CSAT Special Lecture,\" adding \"For 1st-year students to handle 3rd-year coursework, they must have received very intensive education during middle school.\" A high school parent from the Bucheon-Anyang area in Gyeonggi Province criticized a school that makes students ranked in the top 50 study in glass-walled study rooms, calling it inhumane. There were also reports of discriminatory practices such as serving school meals in order of academic rank. A high school parent from the Gangnam 3-gu area reported that if their child's grades don't reach a certain level, parents are restricted from joining volunteer activity groups. Excessive competition-oriented education in front-line middle and high schools was not limited to Seoul's Gangnam [an affluent district in Seoul] or Gyeonggi Province. A parent from Gangwon Province said, \"Many students are forced to participate in supplementary classes because the school says it won't provide self-directed learning certification if they don't participate in after-school supplementary classes.\" In Cheongju, Chungbuk Province, there were reports that schools deduct points from performance assessments [school-based assessment, not standardized exam] if students don't participate in evening self-study. No More Worry About Private Education stated, \"Through directly meeting citizens nationwide and listening to parents' and teachers' opinions in the field, we confirmed that ranking-based educational perspectives are deeply rooted nationwide and widely spread across elementary, middle, and high schools.\" The organization particularly pointed out that \"ranking-based educational practices that should be immediately eliminated are still prevalent, such as dormitory admission based on grades that gives special treatment only to high-achieving students, special classes for top performers, separate study rooms, meals served by grade rank, acceptance banners, and various tests that induce advanced learning.\" No More Worry About Private Education introduced that among the 151 reported cases where they verified facts and requested improvements from schools, unfair competitive education practices were abolished at 23 schools. This organization plans to organize hub meetings in 50 regions nationwide this year to work on improving ranking-based practices by school and monitoring the implementation status of competition-reduction education policies by education offices. An official from No More Worry About Private Education said, \"To alleviate entrance exam suffering and normalize public education, we will work to inspect and evaluate the will and policy implementation status of the Ministry of Education and education offices so that the public can evaluate them in presidential elections and superintendent elections.\""
}

