  "translated_title": "",
  "translated_text": "The copyright for interview materials belongs to SBS Radio. When republishing in full or quoting interviews in news reports, please clearly indicate the channel name and exact program name as follows. Broadcast: Kim Seong-jun's Current Affairs Outlook (FM 103.5 MHz 18:05 ~ 20:00) Host: SBS Anchor Kim Seong-jun Broadcast Date: November 27, 2017 (Monday) Guest: Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education ---- - Expanding students' subject selection rights through customized courses and free course enrollment systems - Based on pilot program results, will gain concrete experience in teacher hiring and educational methods - 60% required subjects, 40% selection of preferred fields - Since universities select majors, this will be effective for university education - University admissions should change according to high school curriculum organization - Detailed analysis needed on how many teachers are required by subject - With the high school credit system, there's no reason to receive advance education through hagwon education  Kim Seong-jun/Host: The Ministry of Education announced today that it will fully introduce the high school credit system, President Moon Jae-in's signature education pledge, starting in 2022, and will begin pilot operations at 100 schools nationwide from next year. The idea is to study like in university even in high school. It's a system where students can take desired subjects and graduate upon completing a certain number of credits. Even before pilot operations begin, voices of both expectation and concern are emerging. In this segment, we'll connect by phone with Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education Lee Jae-jeong, who is already piloting an educational process similar to the high school credit system in Gyeonggi Province, to discuss related matters. Superintendent Lee Jae-jeong, hello.  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: Yes, hello.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: It was last June, wasn't it? You already announced that you would gradually implement a grade-less credit system for high schools, at least in Gyeonggi Province. It's also called the cluster curriculum, I understand. You're already implementing it, right?  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: That's correct. We formed a task force to research high school credit operation plans starting last April. Through curriculum cluster operationsprograms that bundle multiple schools togetherand customized courses and free course enrollment systems, we have been expanding students' subject selection rights.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: You're saying that if they want, students can go to other schools to take classes?  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: Correct. If their school doesn't offer a subject, they can take it together with other schools.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: Although it's been less than a few months, is it going well so far?  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: So far, we're also in pilot operations. The most important thing is that in the Fourth Industrial Revolution era, we must enable students to demonstrate their individual abilities and aptitudes. To allow students to make career choices centered on themselves, it's good to broaden students' options. So we currently have 201 cluster operation schools, 94 schools with customized courses, and 95 subject-focused schools in operation. The evaluation has been quite positive so far.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: To put it simply, unlike the current system where liberal arts students must take predetermined liberal arts subjects and sit in classrooms with teachers rotating in and out, and science students do the same for sciencethis is different. Students who think 'this seems to match my aptitude when I consider my career path, so I want to focus on studying this area to graduate from school' would be given that opportunity. That's what you're saying, right?  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: That's right. In Bucheon, for example, we've made all general high schools subject-focused schools. Depending on the school, students can choose from science, internationalization, arts, foreign languages, and integrated education. Students can choose and enter schools, studying more in those fields and less in other areas. We started this as one process.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: One of the main reasons I'm connecting with you by phone, Superintendent, is not only because I'm curious about how it's being implemented in Gyeonggi Province, but also because similar high school credit systems will be piloted at 100 schools nationwide starting next year, as announced by the Ministry of Education. But as I'll ask again later, KTU [Korean Teachers and Education Workers Union, a left-leaning teachers' organization] is currently opposing this, saying basic concepts haven't even been agreed upon yet, so how can this be introduced? That's why we're even more curious about how it's being implemented in Gyeonggi Province.  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: But KTU [Korean Teachers and Education Workers Union, a left-leaning teachers' organization]'s claim that concepts aren't established domestically is an inappropriate expression. The whole world is moving in this direction. Places like Finland have already comprehensively reorganized their curriculum structure and are moving forward. Moreover, in the Fourth Industrial Revolution, arguments that we must fundamentally overturn the entire structure of what we call curriculum have been emerging for several years now. Actually, I think we're late. It's very fortunate that the government is doing this now.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: Since we don't know well, I'd like to ask about basic curiosities and concerns step by step. For example, there will be students who want to make computers their life's work and want to take more computer-related subjects. To satisfy the needs of such students, many subjects would need to be offered. The question is whether so many subjects can actually be offered, whether the various preparations needed to offer such subjects will be supported, and whether enough teachers will be recruited accordingly. This is what I'm most curious about.  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: Since we're conducting pilot operations, based on the results of these pilot operations, we'll gain concrete experience about which fields require more teacher hiring, which fields need more adjustment, and educational methods. As you mentioned, if a student wants to major in computers, according to the Ministry of Education's announcement, there are required subjects that all students must generally select, which accounts for about 60%. The remaining 40% can be selected from fields they prefer. Under current law, if they select their preferred fields, they can study 20% more, but in this case, they'll do about 40%, so they can select a bit more from their preferred fields. I think there won't be much difficulty in practice.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: You're saying it's naturally not 100% free choice of whatever they want.  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: Yes. And since not all schools can do this, if subjects are offered regionally through cluster systems between schools as I mentioned earlier, students will be able to adequately complete those subjects. Based on our experience so far, we think we need to consider teachers more comprehensively at the regional level, rather than thinking about teachers by individual schools.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: That could work. But another concern is that once students can choose like this, won't there be a prominent tendency to select only subjects advantageous for college entrance exams, regardless of their future careers? How should this concern be addressed?  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: That possibility exists, but since universities actually select majors, if students prepare more in their major fields for university, I think it will be effective for university education. And I think university admissions should change according to high school curriculum organization. Until now, high school education has been somewhat oppressed by university admissions, which was actually a wrong trend. I was also at a university, but universities should have been able to select the personnel they need based on the results of high school education. Since there was no such system, they just did things generally and uniformly, making it difficult for universities to choose as well.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: So this high school credit system isn't just about changes in high school education, but also requires concurrent changes in the university admission system.  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: I think so. So universities can actually receive data to select appropriate students for each major field. Students will first select fields according to their aptitudes, and this can connect from high school education to university education.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: Yes. But how about the teacher numbers issue now? There's talk that the student-to-teacher ratio is too highin other words, there's a shortage of teachers. There's already talk of shortages, but if this high school credit system is implemented, more teachers will be needed. You mentioned clusters earlier, where teachers from nearby schools exchange or enable joint learning, but wouldn't more recruitment still be necessary for full implementation?  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: Our teacher recruitment methods so far have been based on how many teachers to assign per class. Elementary, middle, and high schools were each different. For example, in middle schools in Gyeonggi Province, if there were 10 classes, we generally assigned 17 teachers. We've done it this way, but for high school education going forward, it's not about this approach, but rather about what teachers are needed by subject and field. We should hire appropriate numbers by field. High schools currently hire about 21 teachers for 10 classes. Instead of hiring this way, as you mentioned, it's not about students per teacher, but requires more detailed analysis of how many teachers are needed by each subject. So I don't think it's a big problem. Currently in high schools, there were about 21 teachers for 10 classes, but if we analyze this well during the hiring process and recruit by major fields, I don't think there will be major problems. Second, if future school education moves toward teachers not being experts who teach, but rather coaching teachers who guide students according to their needs  Kim Seong-jun/Host: Making them study on their own, right?  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: Yes. With separate training, I think it's fully possible.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: I understand. Briefly, do you think this high school credit system can also reduce hagwon education costs?  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: I guarantee 100% that there's a way to reduce hagwon education costs. Because if students can study satisfactorily in their major fields in high school and advance to universities with proper school records based on these results, university selection will be much more accurate. Then there's no reason to go to hagwon education to receive advance education.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: I understand. Thank you for your comments today. We'll conclude here.  Lee Jae-jeong, Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education: Yes, thank you. Goodbye.  Kim Seong-jun/Host: We've been speaking with Gyeonggi Superintendent of Education Lee Jae-jeong."
}

